<article>
    <h1>FDA: Pfizer vac&#xAD;cine pro&#xAD;tects within 10 days of first dose</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201210/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-10"><time>2020-12-10</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>WASH­ING­TON • The coro­n­avirus vac­cine made by Pfizer and BioNTech pro­vides strong pro­tec­tion against Covid-19 within about 10 days of the first dose, ac­cord­ing to doc­u­ments pub­lished on Tues­day by the United States’ Food and Drug Ad­min­is­tra­tion (FDA).</p>
    <p>The vac­cine also worked well re­gard­less of a vol­un­teer’s race, weight or age.</p>
    <p>“This is what an A-plus re­port card looks like for a vac­cine,” said Pro­fes­sor Akiko Iwasaki, an im­mu­nol­o­gist at Yale Univer­sity.</p>
    <p>FDA’s vac­cine ad­vi­sory panel will to­day dis­cuss the data in ad­vance of a vote on whether to rec­om­mend au­tho­ri­sa­tion of the vac­cine.</p>
    <p>Pfizer and BioNTech’s largescale clin­i­cal trial be­gan in July with 44,000 vol­un­teers in the US, Brazil and Ar­gentina. Half of them re­ceived the vac­cine, and half were given the placebo.</p>
    <p>New Covid-19 cases ta­pered off in the vac­ci­nated group about 10 days af­ter the first dose. Cases grew steadily in the placebo group. But it is un­clear how long pro­tec­tion from the first dose would last on its own.</p>
    <p>The ef­fi­cacy of the vac­cine af­ter the first dose is about 52 per cent, ac­cord­ing to Dr Wil­liam Gru­ber, se­nior vice-pres­i­dent of Pfizer Vac­cine Clin­i­cal Re­search and De­vel­op­ment. Af­ter the sec­ond dose three weeks later, it is about 95 per cent.</p>
    <p>“Two doses of vac­cine pro­vide max­i­mum pro­tec­tion,” he said.</p>
    <p>While the trial did not find any se­ri­ous ad­verse events caused by the vac­cine, many par­tic­i­pants did ex­pe­ri­ence aches, fevers and other side ef­fects.</p>
    <p>Yes­ter­day Bri­tain’s medicine reg­u­la­tor ad­vised that peo­ple with a his­tory of sig­nif­i­cant al­ler­gic re­ac­tions do not get the Pfiz­erBioNTech vac­cine af­ter two peo­ple re­ported ad­verse ef­fects on the first day of roll-out.</p>
    <p>Na­tional Health Ser­vice med­i­cal di­rec­tor Stephen Powis said two NHS work­ers re­ported ana­phy­lac­toid re­ac­tions as­so­ci­ated with get­ting the shots.</p>


</article>

